Through the course of life, you will meet many many people. You will meet the good one, the bad one. Through it all, you will be lucky and meet friends.
.
And once or twice, you will meet the one who is more than that. The one who you can talk to about the most deep of shit, or the most random and receh kind of stuff. The one who you can be weird with and won't give an eff about how absurd you are, because you all are equally as weird as each other.
.
These are the soul sisters, the one-in-a-kind that you'll be lucky enough to find in life. And the one who you know will always be your supporter, and do things without you asking because they just somehow knew what you needed. All the time.
.
Thank you for being there for me through all the ups-and-downs, through all the happy time and all the rough time. Though we might have our own fallout, thank you for always standing with me, from when we're only such a brat in the 7th grade until now when we're in our 20's (although we don't act like one üòÇ). For always giving me a healthy dose of authenticity and craziness and good times every time we are together. For getting excited about the most unimportant things we often said, but we got excited anyway.
.
And even though we might have our own path in life, at the end of the day, we could just go together and talk about anything at all, not having to pretend or anything and just enjoying it. 
See you in half a year! Godspeed!
.
(Minus @kessyatmadja yang sedang menjadi panitia berdedikasi tinggi üòÇ)

The picture was there, and the girl stared.
And wondered.
.
Wondered if the people on it felt as trapped as she was.
As small as she was feeling. No ground beneath her. No sky above her.
Nothing.
.
The girl wondered, about the probable chances.
That their soul might be captured there.
A little piece of their life, left behind.
Somewhere on that photographs.
Somewhere, someone, had a fragment of their soul, embedded deep on the frame.
.
And she wondered.
Maybe she had taken one too many.
Maybe her soul had been stretched too far away.
Maybe it had been trapped all along.
Fragments of her soul,
A tiny stardust against the eternity.
.
-excerpt from a random story I conjured up on a whim, Pages 23

There was once a girl and the sky.
The girl watched. And the sky bloomed.
And thus the two become friends.
.
Thus the girl talked and the sky would listen.
And the sky shone
and the girl would basked in it.
The two shared witty banters.
They grew ever closer.
And the sky felt it had found home.
.
Thus the girl freaked out.
And ran away.
Shut the door
And spent days away from the light.
Because she never thought of the sky
As anything else but friend.
And maybe she was not ready.
Or maybe she had scarred,
Far too deep for her heart
To be mended by dusk and dawn.
.
So the sky relented
And they grew ever apart,
Never seeing each other
Aside from the windows parted.
And thus the sky accepted
What the girl had decided
And pulled itself away
Hoping the girl would one day
Came out once again.
.
That was when the girl stepped out
From her closed door
And found the sky had grown cold
And the veil of cloud
Was up against the usual blue.
They had grown apart,
Farther than she would have asked.
.
And thus the girl realized;
She had missed
Those bright sky
And the friend
She had taken for granted.
.
-The Everblue, a poem written by yours truly
